body:
Similar boat here. Ubuntu 22.04, X. I opened up an Alacritty terminal when running high dpi mode (laptop screen only) then I plugged in my monitor which lowers the resolution on both the laptop and the monitor, and now the fonts are huge. The mouse cursor when hovering the terminal is also huge. 

It seems that Wezterm the fonts auto adjust in this situation somehow. Wezterm is also hit by the cursor issue though. I didn't reallize the cursor was still an issue when I started writing this message. I wonder if Wezterm is manually adjusting font size?

I don't know if Alacritty and Wezterm can actually be compared here, I just mention it because they both use Rust.

Edit: looks like Wezterm doesn't use winit https://github.com/wez/wezterm/issues/2630#issuecomment-1279794646

Edit2: the winit folks might be taking the position that the app should recheck scaling factors themselves https://github.com/rust-windowing/winit/issues/1377#issuecomment-572410783

Edit 3: I'm not a rust dev, I have no idea about making GUIs, so this is an extreme hack. But I wanted to prove to myself that the app could in theory update the scaling factor, even if manually, so I made this awful abomination and now the scaling factor updates randomishly when changing font size

```
git diff
diff --git a/alacritty/src/display/mod.rs b/alacritty/src/display/mod.rs
index 4d9c1540..6e7e4b94 100644
--- a/alacritty/src/display/mod.rs
+++ b/alacritty/src/display/mod.rs
@@ -1,6 +1,6 @@
 //! The display subsystem including window management, font rasterization, and
 //! GPU drawing.
-
+use std::time::{SystemTime};
 use std::cmp;
 use std::fmt::{self, Formatter};
 use std::mem::{self, ManuallyDrop};
@@ -611,10 +611,12 @@ impl Display {
             let renderer_update = self.pending_renderer_update.get_or_insert(Default::default());
             renderer_update.clear_font_cache = true
         }
-
         // Update font size and cell dimensions.
         if let Some(font) = pending_update.font() {
             let scale_factor = self.window.scale_factor;
+            let duration_since_epoch = SystemTime::now().duration_since(SystemTime::UNIX_EPOCH).unwrap();
+            let scale_factor = if (duration_since_epoch.as_secs() % 2 == 0) {1 as f64} else {2 as f64};
+            println!("funky scale factor {}", scale_factor.to_string());
             let cell_dimensions =
                 Self::update_font_size(&mut self.glyph_cache, scale_factor, config, font);
             cell_width = cell_dimensions.0;
```

With this knowledge, I know we can at least allow for manual scaling which is better than nothing. It also seem there is some caching of the scaling factor within Alacritty that I want to explore.
